snippet.textDisplay: Minecraft and Terraria aren't meant to be or are rivals. Minecraft provides a better sandbox experience while Terraria is a more action/quest based game. Tbh, I don't build in Terraria except for the mandatory home and shelter for my NPC's, an infinite obsidian, and a boss platform. Unlike the comment below I don't see Terraria as a game that allows players to build anything they can think of, and the game runs short of playability after beating all of the hardmode bosses.
snippet.textOriginal: Minecraft and Terraria aren't meant to be or are rivals. Minecraft provides a better sandbox experience while Terraria is a more action/quest based game. Tbh, I don't build in Terraria except for the mandatory home and shelter for my NPC's, an infinite obsidian, and a boss platform. Unlike the comment below I don't see Terraria as a game that allows players to build anything they can think of, and the game runs short of playability after beating all of the hardmode bosses.

snippet.textDisplay: Certainly a great rival to Minecraft imo. While the exploration isn't necessarily as deep, it offers a little more 'game' than 'sandbox' for those of us looking for something a little more exciting, while still allowing us the freedom to build anything within the bounds of our imagination.
snippet.textOriginal: Certainly a great rival to Minecraft imo. snippet.textDisplay:
@MHPL01 Notch admitted on his twitter he was quite enjoying Terraria, actually.

And while in a way it being a 2D clone seems fair, there's far more exploration, combat, and discovery to be had in Terraria - while the actual 'crafting' part is more Minecraft's strength.  In practice, they feel like two very different games.
